{{Infobox film | name = Behind the Burly Q | image = Behind the Burly Q.jpg | alt = <!-- see WP:ALT --> | caption = | director = Leslie Zemeckis | producer = {{ubl|Leslie Zemeckis|Sheri Hellard|[[Robert Zemeckis]]}} | writer = Leslie Zemeckis | starring = | music = Phil Marshall | cinematography = Sheri Hellard | editing = Evan Finn | studio = Mistress, Inc. | distributor = [[First Run Features]] | released = {{Film date|2010|4|23}} | runtime = 98 minutes | country = United States | language = English | budget = | gross = $23,889<ref>{{cite web |title=Behind the Burly Q (2010) |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=behindtheburlyq.htm |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]] |accessdate=20 December 2013}}</ref> }} '''''Behind the Burly Q''''' is a 2010 film documentary examining at the golden age of [[American burlesque]] in the first half of the 20th century.<ref>{{cite AV media |people=Leslie Zemeckis (Director) |title=Behind the Burly Q |medium=DVD |publisher=[[First Run Features]] |asin=B004I45MUC |year=2010}}</ref><ref name=latimes>{{cite news |last=Gelt |first=Jessica |title='Behind the Burly Q' a revealing portrait of burlesque's stars |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2013/jul/06/entertainment/la-et-jc-leslie-zemeckis-20130706 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=6 July 2013}}</ref>
==Synopsis== {{More plot|date=November 2015}} This documentary film about the heyday of burlesque includes interviews with exotic dancers of the time [[April March (dancer)|April March]], Lorraine Lee, Taffy O’Neill, [[Blaze Starr]], [[Tempest Storm]], and [[Kitty West]]; Mike Iannucci, stripper Ann Corio’s husband and producer of “This Was Burlesque”; journalists and authors Nat Bodian, Rachel Schteir, and Janet Davis; and actor [[Alan Alda]], whose father [[Robert Alda]] was a burlesque singer and straight man.
==Reception== Film review aggregator Rotten Tomatoes reports that 78% of critics gave the film a positive review, based on 27 reviews, with an average score of 6.5/10.<ref>{{Rotten Tomatoes|id=behind_the_burly_q}}</ref> Emily Hourican of the ''[[Irish Independent]]'' lauded the film as "an absorbing, moving and cleverly constructed look at the tradition of American burlesque."<ref>{{cite news |first=Emily |last=Hourican |title=Leslie takes peek behind burlesque curtain |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/movies/leslie-takes-peek-behind-burlesque-curtain-26638755.html |work=[[Irish Independent]] |date=March 7, 2010}}</ref> Roger Ebert of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' was less enthusiastic, claiming the film "settles too easily for an editing formula which alternates talking heads, too cursory performance footage and montages of headlines and photographs."<ref>{{cite news |first=Roger |last=Ebert |authorlink=Roger Ebert |title=Behind the Burly-Q |url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/behind-the-burly-q-2010 |work=rogerebert.com |date=18 August 2010}}</ref> Ronnie Scheib of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' said the film's "stories run from raunchy to touching to funny to flat-out incredible.”<ref>{{cite web|last=Scheib|first=Ronnie|title=Review: ‘Behind the Burly Q’|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117942608.html|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>
==Book== In 2013, Skyhorse Publishing released a companion book by Zemeckis, also called ''Behind the Burly Q''.
