{{electronics-stub}}

The '''Muslim social''' is a [[film genre]] in [[Hindi cinema]] that portrays and critiques [[Islamic culture]] in [[India]]. It flourished in the 1950s and 1960s and lasted till the early 1980s. Muslim socials are divided into two categories: "classic Muslim socials" that explore [[nawab]]i culture and focus on upper class or elite Muslim families, and "new wave Muslim socials" that portray middle class Muslim families who experience economic problems, [[discrimination]] and [[communal violence]].<ref>{{cite book |title= Islamicate Cultures of Bombay Cinema |last= Allen |first= Richard|author2=Ira Bhaskar |year= 2009 |publisher= Tulika Books |isbn= 978-81-89487-53-9|pages= 91–92}}</ref> Muslim socials often include [[Filmi-ghazal|ghazal]]s, [[qawwali]]s, [[Urdu poetry]] and expressions, and musical forms commonly associated with Islamic culture.<ref>{{cite book |title= Media and the Transformation of Religion in South Asia |last= Babb |first= Lawrence A. |author2=Susan S. Wadley |year= 1998 |publisher= Motilal Banarsidass |isbn= 81-208-1453-3 |page= 151 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=cgDHFFe7YM8C&pg=PA151&dq|accessdate= 17 March 2010}}</ref> However, lately the label has also been criticized for cultural ghettoization of [[Minority group|minority cinema]]. Director [[M.S. Sathyu]] who made ''[[Garam Hava]]'' (1973), called it "a skewed way to look at cinema. When there is no Hindu social or Christian social, how can there be a Muslim social".<ref name=hindu14>{{cite web | title = Back with the wind |work=The Hindu | url = http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/back-with-the-wind/article6596295.ece |date=November 14, 2014| accessdate = 2014-11-14 }}</ref>
==History== The earliest Muslim socials were made in the 1930s after the advent of [[Sound film|sound]] and continued to be popular until the 1980s. The genre's popularity was partly due to the financial success of [[Mehboob Khan]]'s ''[[Najma (film)|Najma]]'' (1943), which became the blueprint for Muslim socials that followed, which too delved on social issues around Muslim families, no matter what the setting, giving the genre its title.<ref>{{cite book |title= Women, Islam and cinema|last= Dönmez-Colin |first= Gönül |year= 2004 |publisher= Reaktion Books |location= London|isbn= 1-86189-220-9 |page= 93 |pages= |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=pWhZ0hgH80cC&printsec=frontcover |accessdate=17 March 2010}}</ref><ref name=tri/>
Based on the life of [[Mughal Emperor]], [[Jahangir]], ''[[Pukar (1939 film)|Pukar]]'' (1939) made by [[Sohrab Modi]], known for his historicals, is the first notable film in this genre.<ref name=ru189/> Soon Hindi cinema based in [[Mumbai]] became the hub for Muslim socials, and it employed a large number of Muslim producers, director, screenwriters, music directors, lyricists and actors,<ref name=ru189/> most notably [[Mehboob Khan]], [[K. A. Abbas]], [[Kamal Amrohi]], [[Abrar Alvi]], [[Abdul Rashid Kardar]], [[Saadat Hassan Manto]], [[Ismat Chugtai]], [[Ghulam Haider (composer)|Ghulam Haider]], [[Khayyam]], [[Sahir Ludhianvi]], [[Majrooh Sultanpuri]], [[Shakeel Badayuni]], [[Mohammed Rafi]], [[Talat Mahmood]], [[Shamshad Begum]].<ref name=cine/> Numerous films were made about the Mughals, including ''[[Humayun (film)|Humayun]]'' (1945) by [[Mehboob Khan]], ''[[Shahjehan]]'' (1946) by [[Abdul Rashid Kardar]], ''[[Taj Mahal (1963 film)|Taj Mahal]]'' (1963) by M. Sadiq, and ''[[Jahan Ara (film)|Jahan Ara]]'' (1964), however the pinnacle of this royalty theme was ''[[Mughal-e-Azam]]'' (1960) by [[K. Asif]], about [[Akbar]], his son [[Prince Salim]] (later known as Jahangir), and the courtesan [[Anarkali]], who itself became the theme of other films, like ''[[Anarkali (1953 film)|Anarkali]]'' (1953).<ref name=ru189>[[#Ru|Ruthven, 189]]</ref> Another popular theme of the period was centered on the nawabi culture, especially the culture of [[Awadh]], present day [[Lucknow]], it produced films marked by elaborate production, music and highlighting the sophistication of language and lifestyle, like ''[[Mirza Ghalib (film)|Mirza Ghalib]]'' (1954), ''[[Chaudhvin Ka Chand]]'' (1960), ''[[Mere Mehboob]]'' (1963), ''[[Dil Hi To Hai (1963 film)|Dil Hi To Hai]]'' (1963) and ''[[Pakeezah]]'' (1972) by [[Kamal Amrohi]], starring [[Meena Kumari]], which spent over a decade in making.<ref name=cine/><ref name=gu241/>
Thereafter the films in this genre shifted from regal that of fading Nawabi culture - ''[[Bahu Begum]]'' (1967). After experiencing its height in the 1970s, the genre descended to being a mere stereotypical and kitschy representation complete a ''kotha'' of a courtesan or a nawab stricken with poverty. One exception was ''[[Umrao Jaan (1981 film)|Umrao Jaan]]'' (1981) directed by [[Muzaffar Ali]] based on 1905 historical novel ''[[Umrao Jaan Ada]]'' by [[Mirza Hadi Ruswa]].
Musical romances were also prepared in this genre which included [[H. S. Rawail]]'s ''Mere Mehboob'' (1963), ''[[Mehboob Ki Mehndi]]'' (1971) and ''[[Laila Majnu (1976 film)|Laila Majnu]]'' (1976).<ref name=sify>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/h-s-rawail-death-of-a-faded-giant-news-bollywood-kkfvH8fifge.html|title=H.S. Rawail: Death of a faded giant|author=[[Subhash K. Jha]]|publisher=[[sify.com]]|date=September 24, 2004|accessdate=October 5, 2013}}</ref> More over reflecting on the changing times, themes shifted regal to middle class [[North India]]n Muslims, and from mainstream Bollywood to [[parallel cinema]] or the new wave cinema, starting with ''[[Dastak (1970 film)|Dastak]]'' (1970), ''[[Garm Hava]]'' (1973), ''[[Bazaar (1982 film)|Bazaar]]'' (1982) and ''[[Nikaah]]'' (1982). Besides that Ali made ''[[Anjuman (1986 film)|Anjuman]]'' (1986), and [[Saeed Akhtar Mirza]] made ''[[Salim Langde Pe Mat Ro]]'' (1989) and ''[[Naseem (film)|Naseem]]'' (1995). Gradually the genre lost both nuanced depiction of its hey days was imitated by the cinema many Muslim countries, and audiences as well, and few notable additions were made to this genre, and too sporadic.<ref name=tri>{{cite news |title=Muslim Mystique in Indian films |url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2005/20050122/saturday/main1.htm|author=Nirupama Dutt |publisher= The Tribune|date=January 22, 2005 |accessdate=May 21, 2013}}</ref><ref name=ru189/><ref name=gu241/>
The genre resurfaced in works of the screenwriter [[Khalid Mohammed]], ''[[Mammo]]'' (1994), ''[[Sardari Begum]]'' (1996), ''[[Fiza]]'' (2000) and ''[[Zubeidaa]]'' (2001), Mohammed directed ''Fiza'', while the rest were directed by art film master [[Shyam Benegal]], Benegal had previously directed, and ''[[Junoon (1978 film)|Junoon]]'' (1978) set in the [[Indian Rebellion of 1857]], stories with marked political content.<ref name=cine>{{cite web |title=Ghararas To Guns-From The Muslim Social To The Muslim Political |url=http://cineblitz.liveinstyle.com/features/detail/ghararas-to-guns-from-the-muslim-social-to-the-muslim-political |date= December 2012|publisher=Cine Blitz |accessdate=May 22, 2013}}</ref>
